  "prompt": "What is the difference between enum, union and struct in C programming?",
  "response": "Okay, let's break down the differences between `enum`, `union`, and `struct` in C programming.  They are all user-defined data types, but they serve distinct purposes.\n\n**1. `enum` (Enumeration):**\n\n*   **Purpose:** Represents a set of named integer constants.  It's a way to define a type that can only hold one of a predefined set of values.  It enhances readability and maintainability by using meaningful names instead of raw numbers.\n\n*   **Memory Usage:**  An `enum` type typically occupies the same amount of memory as an `int` (or a smaller integer type if the values are small enough).  The compiler chooses the smallest integer type that can represent all the enumeration values.\n\n*   **Members:** Consists of a list of *enumerators*, each of which is associated with an integer value.  If you don't explicitly assign values, the enumerators are assigned values starting from 0 and incrementing by 1.\n\n*   **Example:**\n\n```c\nenum DayOfWeek {\n  SUNDAY,    // 0\n  MONDAY,    // 1\n  TUESDAY,   // 2\n  WEDNESDAY, // 3\n  THURSDAY,  // 4\n  FRIDAY,    // 5\n  SATURDAY   // 6\n};\n\nenum StatusCode {\n    OK = 200,\n    CREATED = 201,\n    BAD_REQUEST = 400,\n    NOT_FOUND = 404,\n    INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR = 500\n};\n\n\nint main() {\n  enum DayOfWeek today = WEDNESDAY;\n  enum StatusCode status = NOT_FOUND;\n\n  printf(\"Today is %d\\n\", today);   // Output: Today is 3\n  printf(\"Status code is %d\\n\", status);  // Output: Status code is 404\n\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n\n*   **Key Characteristics:**\n\n    *   Creates symbolic names for integer values.\n    *   Improves code readability.\n    *   Forces the variable to take only one of the specified values.\n    *   Can be used to represent states, options, or flags.\n\n**2. `union`:**\n\n*   **Purpose:** A `union` is a user-defined data type that can hold *different* data types, but only *one* at a time.  All the members of a union share the *same* memory location. The size of the union is determined by the size of its largest member.\n\n*   **Memory Usage:**  The size of a `union` is equal to the size of its largest member.  This makes it memory-efficient when you need to store different types of data in the same location, but only one type at a given time.\n\n*   **Members:** Consists of a list of members, each of which can have a different data type.\n\n*   **Example:**\n\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n\nunion Data {\n  int i;\n  float f;\n  char str[20];\n};\n\nint main() {\n  union Data data;\n\n  data.i = 10;\n  printf(\"data.i: %d\\n\", data.i);  // Output: data.i: 10\n\n  data.f = 22.5;\n  printf(\"data.f: %f\\n\", data.f);  // Output: data.f: 22.5\n  printf(\"data.i: %d\\n\", data.i);  // Output: data.i: Garbage Value (overwritten by data.f)\n\n  strcpy(data.str, \"C Programming\");\n  printf(\"data.str: %s\\n\", data.str); // Output: data.str: C Programming\n  printf(\"data.i: %d\\n\", data.i);  // Output: data.i: Garbage Value (overwritten by data.str)\n  printf(\"data.f: %f\\n\", data.f);  // Output: data.f: Garbage Value (overwritten by data.str)\n\n  printf(\"Size of union Data: %zu bytes\\n\", sizeof(union Data)); // Output: Size of union Data: 20 bytes (size of str)\n\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n\n*   **Key Characteristics:**\n\n    *   Shares memory among its members.\n    *   Only one member can be actively used at any given time.\n    *   Saves memory if you don't need to store all the members simultaneously.\n    *   Requires careful tracking of which member is currently valid.\n    *   Useful for situations where you have mutually exclusive data types.\n\n**3. `struct` (Structure):**\n\n*   **Purpose:** A `struct` is a user-defined data type that allows you to group together variables of different data types under a single name. It represents a composite data type, where each member of the struct has its own dedicated memory location.\n\n*   **Memory Usage:** The size of a `struct` is (usually) the sum of the sizes of its members.  However, compilers often introduce *padding* to align members on memory boundaries, which can increase the struct's size.  The members are stored sequentially in memory.\n\n*   **Members:** Consists of a list of members (fields), each with its own name and data type.\n\n*   **Example:**\n\n```c\n#include <stdio.h>\n#include <string.h>\n\nstruct Student {\n  char name[50];\n  int age;\n  float gpa;\n};\n\nint main() {\n  struct Student student1;\n\n  strcpy(student1.name, \"Alice\");\n  student1.age = 20;\n  student1.gpa = 3.8;\n\n  printf(\"Name: %s\\n\", student1.name);    // Output: Name: Alice\n  printf(\"Age: %d\\n\", student1.age);      // Output: Age: 20\n  printf(\"GPA: %f\\n\", student1.gpa);      // Output: GPA: 3.8\n\n  printf(\"Size of Student struct: %zu bytes\\n\", sizeof(struct Student)); // Output: Size of Student struct: (something like) 58 bytes (depending on padding)\n\n  return 0;\n}\n```\n\n*   **Key Characteristics:**\n\n    *   Groups together related data of different types.\n    *   Each member has its own independent memory location.\n    *   Allows you to create complex data structures.\n    *   Is widely used to represent objects, records, or entities.\n\n**Summary Table:**\n\n| Feature       | `enum`                                   | `union`                                  | `struct`                                   |\n| ------------- | ----------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |\n| Purpose       | Represents a set of named integer constants | Holds different data types, one at a time | Groups related data of different types    |\n| Memory        | Typically size of `int`                    | Size of the largest member               | Sum of member sizes (plus possible padding) |\n| Members       | Enumerators (integer constants)          | Fields with different types             | Fields with different types             |\n| Usage         | Representing options, states, flags        | Saving memory, mutually exclusive data   | Representing objects, records, entities   |\n| Simultaneous Data | No, represents a single choice          | No, only one member can be active        | Yes, all members are accessible          |\n\n**In short:**\n\n*   Use `enum` when you want to define a set of named integer constants (e.g., status codes, days of the week).\n*   Use `union` when you want to save memory and only need to store one of several possible data types at a time.  Be careful to track which member is currently valid.\n*   Use `struct` when you want to group together related data of different types and need to access all the members simultaneously.\n\nUnderstanding these differences is crucial for writing efficient and well-structured C code.  Choose the data type that best suits the needs of your program.\n",
